&lt;p&gt;In this example, we use the &amp;ldquo;HandleFunc&amp;rdquo; function of the &amp;ldquo;http&amp;rdquo; package to specify a function that will be called whenever a request is received. We then create a Goroutine inside this function to handle the request concurrently. This allows the server to handle multiple requests concurrently, improving its performance and scalability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another common use case for concurrency in Go is data processing. Suppose we have a large dataset that needs to be processed and analyzed. By using Goroutines, we can divide the dataset into smaller chunks and process them concurrently, leading to faster processing times. Here is an example of how this might be done:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-code-block hx:relative hx:mt-6 hx:first:mt-0 hx:group/code"&gt;
